Finding persons of interest in the Enron scandal with Machine Learning¶

Enron Corporation is an energy company based in Houston Texas. In 2000, it was one of the largest companies in the United States. By 2002, it had collapsed into bankruptcy due to widespread corporate fraud. In the resulting Federal investigation, a significant amount of typically confidential information entered into the public record, including tens of thousands of emails and detailed financial data for top executives.

This project will attempt to identify the person of interest (POI) in the Enron scandal through a series of steps:

1. Understanding the Dataset and Question¶

  • Data Exploration
  • Outlier Investigation

2. Optimize Feature Selection/Engineering¶

  • Create new features
  • Intelligently select features

3. Pick and Tune an Algorithm¶

  • Examine Naive Bayes
  • Examine Decision Tree
  • Examine K Nearest Neighbors
  • Examine and tune Support Vector Machine
  • Examine Random Forest
  • Pick an algorithm
  • Tuning Decision Tree
  • Tuning Linear SVM
  • Tuning Random Forest
  • Classifier Comparison Results

4. Validate and Evaluate¶

  • Final Decision Tree Results
  • Viewing the tree
  • Confusion matrix
  • Classification report

Learn more about the Enron scandal

The observed Enron dataset has a total of 22 features. These are a combination of financial and email attributes and poi. Investigating these features will help us understand which features are highly correlated or irrelevant to build a more effective algorithm.

"Good feature subsets contain features highly correlated with the classification, yet uncorrelated to each other"

Create new features:¶

"fraction_from_poi" : the proportion of sent messages from poi to a person
"fraction_to_poi" : the proportion of sent messages from a person to poi

Here we take the proportion of the from and to poi from the total emails to measure the relatonship. We will assume that if there is no emails to or from poi then NaN values will be replaced with 0.

In [28]:
# Take the ratio from total messages
clean_df["fraction_to_poi"] = clean_df["from_poi_to_this_person"]/clean_df["to_messages"]
clean_df["fraction_from_poi"] = clean_df["from_this_person_to_poi"]/clean_df["from_messages"]
# clean_df.head().T
# Fill in NaNs
clean_df = clean_df.fillna(0)
my_dict = clean_df.set_index("name").T
my_dict_e = clean_df.set_index("name").T

3 Pick and Tune an Algorithm¶

Before testing any algorithm, using a dummy classifier will provide an sanity check for future testing. The dummy classifier uses simple rules to implement strategies:

  • stratified generates random predictions by respecting the training set class distribution.
  • most_frequent always predicts the most frequent label in the training set.
  • prior always predicts the class that maximizes the class prior.
  • uniform generates predictions uniformly at random.
  • constant always predicts a constant label that is provided by the user.

Splitting the dataset¶

One methodological mistake is performing learning parameters and predicting function on the same dataset.Therefore it is important that we split our data into training and testing sets. Overfitting happens when we use the same dataset to train and predict because the algorithm is accustom to previously seen data. Splitting the data will all some variance in which the algorithm is expose to new information. Gaging the model performance this way is similar to a real life situation. Here we will reserve 30% for testing and 70% for training. This will also help speed up our testing time.

In [40]:

    data_e, labels_e, test_size = 0.3, random_state=42)

Get a baseline from different classifiers¶

We will be evaluating our classifiers mainly through two metrics. These are precision and recall.

Metric definition

Precision: True Positive / (True Positive + False Positive)
Out of all the items labeled as positive, how many truly belong to the positive class.

Recall: True Positive / (True Positive + False Negative)
Out of all the items that are truly positive, how many were correctly classified as positive. Or simply, how many positive items were 'recalled' from the dataset.

When we examine the classifiers, we will use a simple pipeline. The combination consist of a data standardizing, feature selection method and an algorithm below.

Standardization:

  • Minmax scaler
  • Standard scaler
  • Robust scaler

Feature selection:

  • K best
  • PCA

After seeing some interesting results from various classifiers, you're probably wondering..."Can we make any of the above classifiers perform better?" Well, we never know for sure but it's always worth a try! We will dig a little deeper into the selected classifiers' hyperparameters. So our goal here is to set these hyperparameters to their optimal values that will give us the best performance with the given dataset.

The best performance for this case would be to maximize the precision and recall scores. As these scores measure how "precise" and how "selective" theh model is. We want both of these scores to be above 30%. This means that the model is 30% correct when predicting the Enron employee who is a poi or a non-poi. We will use GridsearchCV from sci-kit learn to accomplish this task.

With promising scores from the decision tree classifier right out of the box, I want to see if tuning will increase the precision and recall scores.

I will also extend the tuning of SVM to use the LinearSVM classifier. With LinearSVM, we will test out an embedded mothod LASSO as part of feature selection. LASSO is a regulation or penalties for using additional features in the model. Hopefully this will improve the model's learning ability with the skrewed dataset. Lastly, we will look at Random Forest.

Tuning Decision Tree¶

Note: From the above results, the decision tree tend to overfit easily with high dimension data because it's a low bias but high variance classifier. As a way to lower variance, we'll train many models and averaging with StratefiedShuffleSplit.It is important for us to get the right number of features for this classifier. We have tried kbest, let's also try PCA to reduce the number of features and use a robust scaler to standardize the skewed dataset.

Standardizing data:¶

  • Minmaxscaler: between a given minimum and maximum value so that the maximum absolute value of each feature is scaled to unit size. Minmax performs better than the standard scaler.
  • RobustScaler: this scaler removes the median and scales the data according to the IQR.

Feature selection:¶

  • SelectKbest: improves model learning ability. We will try a range of k values which is the range of our features list (19).
  • PCA: reduce feature dimensions

Decision Tree hyperparameters:¶

  • max_depth: control the size of the tree to prevent overfitting.
  • min_samples_splits: control the number of samples at a leaf node. A very small number will usually mean the tree will overfit, whereas a large number will prevent the tree from learning the data.
  • min_samples_leafs: guarantees a minimum number of samples in a leaf
  • criterion: measure the quality of a split. Gini impurity and entropy for the information gain.
  • splitter: strategy used to choose the split at each node. best to choose the best split and random to choose the best random split

Cross validation:¶

  • StratifiedShuffleSplit: Since the full dataset consist of 18 pois vs 112 non-pois, when splitting the data this cross validator will preserve the same percentagefor each label as the complete set.

  • Combo3: Minmax, kbest, and pca

  • Combo6: Kbest

Feature combos:¶

  • Combo_features5: using minmax scaler and pca

Linear SVC hyperparameters:¶

  • C : Penalty parameter C of the error term.
  • loss : hinge is the standard SVM loss (used e.g. by the SVC class) while squared_hinge is the square of the hinge loss.
  • penalty : Specifies the norm used in the penalization. The l2 penalty is the standard used in SVC. The l1 leads to coef_ vectors that are sparse.
  • class_weight : balanced mode uses the values of y to automatically adjust weights inversely proportional to class frequencies in the input data as n_samples / (n_classes * np.bincount(y))

3. Examine and tune Random Forest¶

Taking the decision tree to the next level, this meta estimator fits a number of decision tree classifiers on various sub-samples of the dataset and use the averages to improve the predictive accuracy and control over-fitting. This also allows it to rank features and enable some decisions in tree to perform better.

Random Forest hyperparameters:¶

  • n_estimators : the number of trees in the forest.
  • criterion : measure the quality of a split with gini for the Gini impurity and entropy for the information gain.
  • max_features : decides how many features each tree in the RF considers at each split.

Classifier Results Comparison¶

Throughout the tuning process, I found that it is easy to over tune the classifiers as you experiment with different combinations to find the best pipeline but the results are not always better. On the contrary, under tunning an classifier also have a similar effect. When trying out different scalers, feature selection methods and a classifier without being specific about the hyperparameters or using a wide enough range, random search/grid search will also be limited to these settings.

Decision Tree classifier:¶

I used a combinations of feature selection methods with the same parameter settings. The best combination so far is using a minmax scaler and combined it with kbest to select the features. I've tried both the standard scaler and the minmax scaler with kbest prior to tuning and noticed that the minmax scaler performed slighly better the standard scaler. Both methods rescale the features, but the minmax scaler normalizes the skewed dataset using a range of [0,1]. This resulted in a smaller standard diviation which minimizes the effect of outliers and increases the decision tree performance.

After testing the scalers, I started testing the k range and slowly tune the parameters of the decision tree. As I add each parameter, the performance drops because there are too many parameters for gridsearch to search eventhough I only used a 10 fold cross validation. I got better luck with the randomized search but one caveat is that the results were inconsistent because it look like random search chooses the first best score it sees.

LinearSVC classifier:¶

Initially, I started examining with SVM but it throws an error with the test_classifier module. Then I created a pipeline using a scaler, kbest, and pca without any tuning to get a baseline. However, the classifier tester throws an error. So I started tuning the k range to select k features. Like the decision tree, I also used a range from 1-19 which consist of all the possible features available. C and gamma were tested after k range because this influence shape the decision boundary and weights of each data point. The results were surprising low. It was the worse model I tested.

After trying various C and gamma values as suggested by sci-kit learn, the model finally came back with better results. At this point I wanted to add penalties for using features into the model. Then I started testing with the linear SVM model. Aside from changing a few parameters to adapt to this model, I kept the same C values. After adding the penalties, the model returned a really promising f1 along with higher precision and recall scores!

Random Forest classifier:¶

Building on top of the decision tree classifier, random forest performed extremely well proir to tuning. I tried a few feature combinations and tested the robust scaler to remove the median and scale the data to the IQR. This resulted in better scores but recall dropped. Using a minmax scaler and kbest didn't really improved the scores much but the drawback is the run time.

Overall, the decision tree classifier performed better after a few tuning. Although it doesn't have the best scores in all categories, the precision and recall scores were in close range to each other. It doesn't have a high bias or high variance to the data and still get an f1 above 0.4. Although both the linear SVC and random forest did perform better with the f1 score and have high level of false positives (can predict poi correctly), they have high false negatives as well (predict pois when person is not-poi).

Classifier Precision Recall F1
Decision Tree Pipeline4 0.59595 0.47050 0.52585
LinearSVM Pipeline2 0.43765 0.73000 0.54723
Random Forest Pipeline2 0.74600 0.39650 0.51779

Based on these results, the decision tree and the random forest classifier is more on the conservativeside. Both of their precision scores are higher than recall. On the contrary, linear svm is more flexible where the recall score is higher than the precision score.

Depending on our end goal, each model can serve a different purpose. In this case, the random forest pipeline results could be used to identify innocent employees and linear SVC can apply to flag all suspicious Enron employees for further investigation. In our case, we are looking for a balance and the decision tree is in between these two extremes. Thus it is the model that best suits this dataset.

More info on l1 parameter

What Adaboost?¶

Adaboost is meta-algorithm which improves the output of other weak learners by combining them into a weighted sum that represents the final output of the boosted classifier. With an imbalance dataset, this could help the decision tree classifier.

For Adaboost, there are two types of parameter to be tuned decision tree based and boosting parameters. We will test the learning rate and estimator with the decision tree best paramerters.

Ada parameters:

  1. learning rate:
    • This determines the impact of each tree on the final outcome.
    • Lower values are generally preferred as they make the model robust to the specific characteristics of tree and thus allowing it to generalize well.
    • Lower values would require higher number of trees to model all the relations and will be computationally expensive.
  2. n_estimators: The number of sequential trees to be modeled.

avg / total       0.92      0.92      0.91       126

For cross validation, I choose to use Stratifiedshufflesplit iterator. Since this dataset exhibit a large imbalance in the distribution of the target classes, stratified sampling is used to ensure that relative class frequencies is preserved in each train and validation fold.

Using the confusion matrix and the classification report. We are able to see how the final decision tree model performs on the training/testing set as well as the whole dataset. The matrix is a 2x2 which means that we have two classes. Either an employee at Enron is a poi or not a poi.

  • True Positives (TP): we correctly predicted that the Enron employee is poi
  • True Negatives (TN): we correctly predicted that the Enron employee is not poi
  • False Positives (FP): we incorrectly predicted that the Enron employee is poi (a "Type I error")
  • False Negatives (FN): we incorrectly predicted that the Enron employee is not poi (a "Type II error")

In conclusion, I was able to get an accuracy score of 87% after validating with the test_classifier function. This means that out of all the predictions, I can only be sure that 87% are correct. The precision score indicate how "precise" the model is when predicting enron employees who are a poi. A recall score is how "selective" the model is in predicting Enron employees who are poi. In this case, our model is only precise 59% of the time and it's correctly predicted those who are not pois 50% of the time.

Overall, tuning the classifier parameters did help us build a more effective model but this is computationally expensive and very time consuming. We cannot assume a certain parameters or using a meta-algorithm will improve the model. In the case of using Adaboost above, we actually see the performance dropped.

For future work, I would like to incorporate email data into the dataset. By implement "a bag of word" to create new features, this could possibly identify communication patterns that will help our model be more precise and yield better predictions. We could also iuncorporate a recursive feature elimination method into the pipeline to see how the classifier perform.
